00:10:18,184 --> 00:10:22,254
the official opening of the confernece, Allerton Conference

181
00:10:22,254 --> 00:10:25,725
we can, uh, eh,
continue with the program,

182
00:10:25,725 --> 00:10:32,164
and, eh, and we have a very distinguished, eh, eh, speaker,

183
00:10:32,164 --> 00:10:38,637
eh, to, uh, eh, for this, eh, kick-off evening,

184
00:10:38,637 --> 00:10:41,007
and-and this is
something special.

185
00:10:41,007 --> 00:10:42,141
Allerton Conference,

186
00:10:42,141 --> 00:10:44,944
for those of you who have attended in the past,

187
00:10:44,944 --> 00:10:46,946
has always been for three days

188
00:10:46,946 --> 00:10:50,516
and all events were held
out in Monticello,

189
00:10:50,516 --> 00:10:53,252
and because of this
50th anniversary

190
00:10:53,252 --> 00:10:59,058
we decided to, eh, have
a kick-off event here on campus

191
00:10:59,058 --> 00:11:03,262
and so that we can attract, uh, people who maybe normally

192
00:11:03,262 --> 00:11:05,931
would not have
gone out to Allerton.

193
00:11:05,931 --> 00:11:10,836
And, eh, and, and we wanted to pick someone, uh,

194
00:11:10,836 --> 00:11:16,909
who is, uh, who will talk to the importance of this occasion.

195
00:11:16,909 --> 00:11:23,582
And, eh, I'm very pleased, eh, eh, to, eh, have, eh,

196
00:11:23,582 --> 00:11:27,787
Karl Astrom from
Lund University of Sweden,

197
00:11:27,787 --> 00:11:30,122
eh, to be the keynote speaker

198
00:11:30,122 --> 00:11:33,793
or the Jubilee Lecturer
this evening.

199
00:11:33,793 --> 00:11:38,531
Eh, he is a world renown control
scientist and engineer

200
00:11:38,531 --> 00:11:40,266
and educator,

201
00:11:40,266 --> 00:11:42,668
and I can take
a full hour, actually,

202
00:11:42,668 --> 00:11:44,937
to talk about his accomplishments,

203
00:11:44,937 --> 00:11:46,672
his impact on the field,

204
00:11:46,672 --> 00:11:50,109
not only on the control field but-but-but across the board

205
00:11:50,109 --> 00:11:55,047
and, eh, eh, communications, eh, and-and computing,

206
00:11:55,047 --> 00:11:58,717
those that-that are really
the topics

207
00:11:58,717 --> 00:12:00,853
and areas that are covered Aller-at

208
00:12:00,853 --> 00:12:02,521
the Allerton Conference.

209
00:12:02,521 --> 00:12:07,426
So let me say just a-a few brief, eh, words on, uh,

210
00:12:07,426 --> 00:12:10,529
Karl's background and-and
some of his achievements.

211
00:12:10,529 --> 00:12:13,265
As I said, I won't be
able to cover everything.

212
00:12:13,265 --> 00:12:14,834
He was educated at

213
00:12:14,834 --> 00:12:18,170
the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.

214
00:12:18,170 --> 00:12:21,607
During his studies, he worked on
inertial navigation

215
00:12:21,607 --> 00:12:25,377
for Research Institute
of National Defense.

216
00:12:25,377 --> 00:12:28,848
After working for IBM research
for five years,

217
00:12:28,848 --> 00:12:33,285
he was appointed Professor of the Chair of Automatic Control

218
00:12:33,285 --> 00:12:37,590
at Lund Institute of Technology, or Lund University,

219
00:12:37,590 --> 00:12:39,658
where he established
a new department.

220
00:12:39,658 --> 00:12:44,130
From 2000 'til 2010
he was a professor

221
00:12:44,130 --> 00:12:47,566
at the University of California in Santa Barbara,

222
00:12:47,566 --> 00:12:50,569
and he is currently back at
Lund University

223
00:12:50,569 --> 00:12:52,705
as a, as a senior professor.

224
00:12:52,705 --> 00:12:56,509
Uh, he has broad interest in control including,

225
00:12:56,509 --> 00:13:00,179
stochastic control, modeling, system identification,

226
00:13:00,179 --> 00:13:02,181
adaptive control,
computer control,

227
00:13:02,181 --> 00:13:04,650
and computer-aided
control engineering.

228
00:13:04,650 --> 00:13:09,889
He is listed in the ISI,
ISA Highly Cited

229
00:13:09,889 --> 00:13:12,858
and-and he has
the Adarsh number three.

230
00:13:12,858 --> 00:13:16,228
For those of you who don't
know what that means,

231
00:13:16,228 --> 00:13:20,166
ask your neighbor,
but after the lecture.

232
00:13:20,166 --> 00:13:22,768
And, uh, two,
he has seven books,

233
00:13:22,768 --> 00:13:24,737
and two of these books

234
00:13:24,737 --> 00:13:28,674
have received the prestigious Harold Chestnut Textbook Prize

235
00:13:28,674 --> 00:13:32,178
from the International Federation of Automatic Control.

236
00:13:32,178 --> 00:13:36,382
And one of his papers on
self-tuning control,

237
00:13:36,382 --> 00:13:39,585
which is very well known,
very well cited,

238
00:13:39,585 --> 00:13:42,254
which was co-authored
with Wittenmark,

239
00:13:42,254 --> 00:13:44,690
eh, again from Lund University,

240
00:13:44,690 --> 00:13:49,195
was selected for the IEEE book on control theory.

241
00:13:49,195 --> 00:13:52,865
This was the millennium, eh, book on Control Theory,

242
00:13:52,865 --> 00:13:55,201
25 Seminal Papers,

243
00:13:55,201 --> 00:13:59,338
eh, covering the period
1932 and 1981.

244
00:13:59,338 --> 00:14:06,145
There were only 25 papers that
were picked, eh, er-eh, out of,

245
00:14:06,145 --> 00:14:08,314
from a pool of thousands
of papers,

246
00:14:08,314 --> 00:14:10,482
and-and this was one of those.

247
00:14:10,482 --> 00:14:12,318
Eh, he has several patents,

248
00:14:12,318 --> 00:14:15,654
and one of them for automatic tuning of PID controllers,

249
00:14:15,654 --> 00:14:19,325
which he holds jointly
with-with Hagglund,

250
00:14:19,325 --> 00:14:20,826
eh, and that has led

251
00:14:20,826 --> 00:14:24,129
to substantial
industrial production.

252
00:14:24,129 --> 00:14:26,765
Eh, Karl is a member
of the Royal Society,

