283
00:16:19,244 --> 00:16:22,681
Um, it's certainly a great honor for me to speak

284
00:16:22,681 --> 00:16:24,683
on this fantastic location

285
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:26,719
of the celebration
of the Allerton Conference.

286
00:16:26,719 --> 00:16:28,721
So, I would like to
thank you very much

287
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:30,856
for inviting me to do this.

288
00:16:30,856 --> 00:16:35,194
And, em, Tamer asked me to give a broad picture of control,

289
00:16:35,194 --> 00:16:37,663
and I was brave enough
to take this picture.

290
00:16:37,663 --> 00:16:39,865
There should actually be
a sub-line here saying,

291
00:16:39,865 --> 00:16:41,500
"a personal reflection."

292
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:44,470
So remember what I'm saying here are my personal views.

293
00:16:44,470 --> 00:16:46,572
They're certainly
not universal truth.

294
00:16:49,007 --> 00:16:52,845
So, eh, control has been around for a long time,

295
00:16:52,845 --> 00:16:57,082
but it really started to grow in connection with the development

296
00:16:57,082 --> 00:16:58,083
of the industries.

297
00:16:58,083 --> 00:17:01,653
Eh, it was sometimes
an enabling technology,

298
00:17:01,653 --> 00:17:05,824
but one didn't recognize that there were lots of similarities

299
00:17:05,824 --> 00:17:08,927
between for example, process control, telecommunications,

300
00:17:08,927 --> 00:17:10,896
flight control, etc.

301
00:17:10,896 --> 00:17:14,466
And it became an engineering discipline in the 1940s,

302
00:17:14,466 --> 00:17:18,570
eh, and it has been developing very, very rapidly.

303
00:17:18,570 --> 00:17:22,674
And today we have lots
and lots of applications

304
00:17:22,674 --> 00:17:25,010
and also some
very interesting challenges.

305
00:17:26,912 --> 00:17:30,482
Eh, there have recently been a
couple of studies

306
00:17:30,482 --> 00:17:31,884
of broad pictures of control.

307
00:17:31,884 --> 00:17:34,920
For example, the IEEE
Control Systems Society

308
00:17:34,920 --> 00:17:37,956
has published a book called The Impact of Control Technology,

309
00:17:37,956 --> 00:17:39,691
which is available on the web,

310
00:17:39,691 --> 00:17:42,895
and in connection with
the year eh-two, eh-2000

311
00:17:42,895 --> 00:17:44,897
there were a couple
of books presented

312
00:17:44,897 --> 00:17:47,699
that gave a perspective of engineering and control,

313
00:17:47,699 --> 00:17:49,334
uh, in this century,

314
00:17:49,334 --> 00:17:51,170
and I listed a few of them there

315
00:17:51,170 --> 00:17:52,337
and we'll come back
to them later.

316
00:17:54,173 --> 00:17:55,474
One thing,

317
00:17:55,474 --> 00:17:58,410
that has been a hallmark
of the control community

318
00:17:58,410 --> 00:18:00,446
is a solid foundation.

319
00:18:00,446 --> 00:18:03,749
And I've always been wanting to
have an illustration of this

320
00:18:03,749 --> 00:18:07,920
and by accident I found this
in Montreal this summer.

321
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:09,888
This beautiful building here

322
00:18:09,888 --> 00:18:12,591
happens to be an insurance building in Montreal.

323
00:18:12,591 --> 00:18:14,193
And you look at this beaut,

324
00:18:14,193 --> 00:18:17,529
it was one of the most beautiful buildings in Montreal.

325
00:18:17,529 --> 00:18:20,799
But this tower fell down

326
00:18:20,799 --> 00:18:23,902
because the foundations
were not so good.

327
00:18:23,902 --> 00:18:26,271
They had put in wooden pillars
in the ground

328
00:18:26,271 --> 00:18:28,273
and then they started to rot.

329
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:31,343
So, what I'm saying here, even
if you have a beautiful house,

330
00:18:31,343 --> 00:18:34,279
unless the foundations
are solid,

331
00:18:34,279 --> 00:18:35,314
eh, it's gonna tumble down.

332
00:18:35,314 --> 00:18:37,115
So I'm very proud to say

333
00:18:37,115 --> 00:18:39,117
that this has been
a hallmark of control

334
00:18:39,117 --> 00:18:41,887
and you will see this logo popping up here and there.

335
00:18:44,423 --> 00:18:46,825
I've called control
the hidden technology.

336
00:18:46,825 --> 00:18:48,994
Eh, it's widely used,

337
00:18:48,994 --> 00:18:50,195
it's very successful,

338
00:18:50,195 --> 00:18:51,330
it's seldom talked about

339
00:18:51,330 --> 00:18:53,332
except when there's a disaster, you know.

340
00:18:53,332 --> 00:18:56,835
When a reactor blows up,
when the airplane crashes.

341
00:18:56,835 --> 00:18:58,837
And I've often
been wondering why.

342
00:18:58,837 --> 00:19:02,608
And I think it's much easier to
talk about devices than ideas.

343
00:19:02,608 --> 00:19:05,711
It's much easier to say,
will a computer fix that

344
00:19:05,711 --> 00:19:08,547
than the ideas
that are behind it.

345
00:19:08,547 --> 00:19:09,548
And also I think

346
00:19:09,548 --> 00:19:11,884
we have something to blame ourselves for.

347
00:19:11,884 --> 00:19:14,419
We have been very bad at
telling what control is

348
00:19:14,419 --> 00:19:16,288
to our fellow scientists

349
00:19:16,288 --> 00:19:21,460
and also, em, to our colleagues and to the general public.

350
00:19:21,460 --> 00:19:24,630
Eh, so therefore,
I have advised our students,

351
00:19:24,630 --> 00:19:26,965
this is something
that we have done badly

352
00:19:26,965 --> 00:19:29,801
and you in the next generation now have to do it.

353
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:31,837
So I think Intel
did it very well

354
00:19:31,837 --> 00:19:33,805
with this sort of Intel inside, y'know.

355
00:19:33,805 --> 00:19:35,974
So we should have something
like Control inside.

356
00:19:35,974 --> 00:19:37,476
So that would be one symbol.

357
00:19:37,476 --> 00:19:39,144
And then we should remember, y'know,

358
00:19:39,144 --> 00:19:41,480
to keep the foundations okay.

359
00:19:41,480 --> 00:19:44,316
And if we do this, things would
be very well here in the future.

360
00:19:45,317 --> 00:19:46,885
So what will I do now?

361
00:19:46,885 --> 00:19:48,420
Well I have a very
simple outline.

362
00:19:48,420 --> 00:19:50,322
I-its exactly follows the title.

363
00:19:50,322 --> 00:19:52,858
The past, the present,
the future,

364
00:19:52,858 --> 00:19:54,860
and then I will do
a little summary.

365
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:56,061
So now let's do the past.

366
00:19:57,396 --> 00:19:59,164
Eh, control is a young field.

367
00:19:59,164 --> 00:20:02,768
Ehm, it's a little bit older than the Allerton Conference.

368
00:20:02,768 --> 00:20:08,473
Eh, and-em, eh, so it's useful
to think about this.

369
00:20:08,473 --> 00:20:09,641
We are not matured, y'know.

370
00:20:09,641 --> 00:20:14,012
We're a little bit more
than teenagers but barely.

371
00:20:14,012 --> 00:20:16,648
Eh, there's been e-early use
of control in many fields.

372
00:20:16,648 --> 00:20:19,351
In governors for machines,
in process controls,

373
00:20:19,351 --> 00:20:21,653
in vehicle control,
and communication.

374
00:20:21,653 --> 00:20:24,556
As I said before, people didn't
realize it was the same thing

375
00:20:24,556 --> 00:20:30,162
until we got the Servomechanism
Theory around, say, 1940, 1950.

376
00:20:30,162 --> 00:20:32,631
And this had
tremendous consequences.

377
00:20:32,631 --> 00:20:34,967
Education on control spread
like wildfire

378
00:20:34,967 --> 00:20:37,536
in all engineering education

379
00:20:37,536 --> 00:20:40,505
and I think everybody would have been proud a-uh, about this.

380
00:20:40,505 --> 00:20:42,741
But around 1960, y'know,

381
00:20:42,741 --> 00:20:44,977
about the time the Allerton Conference started,

382
00:20:44,977 --> 00:20:47,512
there was a paradigm shift.

383
00:20:47,512 --> 00:20:50,082
And we got to tackle
the second phase in control

384
00:20:50,082 --> 00:20:51,883
that I will talk a lot about.

385
00:20:51,883 --> 00:20:53,885
And I think what we're
experience now

386
00:20:53,885 --> 00:20:55,053
is the third phase.

387
00:20:55,053 --> 00:20:56,555
And I'm not so sure about this

388
00:20:56,555 --> 00:21:00,359
so that's why I put
a question mark over there.

389
00:21:00,359 --> 00:21:01,493
So let's now do something.

390
00:21:01,493 --> 00:21:03,562
Let's look at power generation.

391
00:21:03,562 --> 00:21:05,931
Y'know, you start to
generate electric power

392
00:21:05,931 --> 00:21:07,733
and if you were using AC

393
00:21:07,733 --> 00:21:10,702
you wanted to generate it
with constant frequency.

394
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:11,703
The solution to this

395
00:21:11,703 --> 00:21:13,705
was that you introduced a turbine controller

396
00:21:13,705 --> 00:21:17,075
which is a classic watt
governor that was, eh,

397
00:21:17,075 --> 00:21:19,077
y'know, these two wheels
start spinning around.

398
00:21:19,077 --> 00:21:21,413
If they go-go, eh, if go fast,

399
00:21:21,413 --> 00:21:24,116
you-you, eh, reduce
the amount of water

400
00:21:24,116 --> 00:21:26,685
that's coming in, etc.

401
00:21:26,685 --> 00:21:31,490
The side effect of this is that whenever you use feedback,

402
00:21:31,490 --> 00:21:33,358
you run the risk of instability.

403
00:21:33,358 --> 00:21:35,861
And that happened when people
started to experiment with this,

404
00:21:35,861 --> 00:21:37,696
so you need it to have
stability theory.

405
00:21:37,696 --> 00:21:39,031
And there were
a number of people,

406
00:21:39,031 --> 00:21:41,600
that you can see
in the bottom of the slide

407
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:42,601
who contributed to this.

408
00:21:42,601 --> 00:21:45,504
There you see from-from left to right you see Maxwell,

409
00:21:45,504 --> 00:21:47,506
who actually wrote one
of the early papers

410
00:21:47,506 --> 00:21:48,674
of analysis of control systems,

411
00:21:48,674 --> 00:21:51,009
Routh, a British mathematician,

412
00:21:51,009 --> 00:21:53,345
Stodola, a Swiss
turbine engineer,

413
00:21:53,345 --> 00:21:56,415
Hurwitz, a sw-a Swiss mathematician,

414
00:21:56,415 --> 00:21:59,851
Vyshnegradski, a Russian engineer, and Lyapunov.

415
00:21:59,851 --> 00:22:02,287
So there was a whole lo-eh-slough of people

416
00:22:02,287 --> 00:22:04,322
who were developing
stability theory.

417
00:22:05,590 --> 00:22:09,261
Let's move to another
field, process control.

418
00:22:09,261 --> 00:22:12,364
Typical problem was a chemical
process to keep temperatures,

419
00:22:12,364 --> 00:22:14,800
to keep pressures,
etc. constant.

420
00:22:14,800 --> 00:22:16,802
The solution to this
was the PID controller.

421
00:22:16,802 --> 00:22:19,438
There were some
nice side effects.

422
00:22:19,438 --> 00:22:22,340
We got an industrial
communication standard,

423
00:22:22,340 --> 00:22:25,610
consisting of plastic tubes
of given dimensions

424
00:22:25,610 --> 00:22:27,813
and the agreement that you should propagate signals

425
00:22:27,813 --> 00:22:31,383
by pressures between
3 and 15 psi.

426
00:22:31,383 --> 00:22:33,385
And then you had
standard instruments

427
00:22:33,385 --> 00:22:35,387
and standard devices
that you connected.

428
00:22:35,387 --> 00:22:37,956
Course with the day's
communication standard, eh,

429
00:22:37,956 --> 00:22:39,958
it's not too good
and not too fast,

430
00:22:39,958 --> 00:22:41,793
but at least it was a standard.

431
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:44,930
We also got two new rules
to tune the PID controllers.

432
00:22:46,364 --> 00:22:48,366
Flight Control.

433
00:22:48,366 --> 00:22:50,268
Question is how to fly?

434
00:22:50,268 --> 00:22:53,905
And one reason that the Wright
Brothers succeeded

435
00:22:53,905 --> 00:22:56,875
was that they
understood dynamics.

436
00:22:56,875 --> 00:22:59,845
And they designed an airplane that was easy to maneuver

437
00:22:59,845 --> 00:23:02,614
but was not terribly stable.

438
00:23:02,614 --> 00:23:05,283
Many other people designed
stable airplanes

439
00:23:05,283 --> 00:23:07,486
that were difficult to maneuver.

440
00:23:07,486 --> 00:23:10,489
Em, a side effect
of this is that, em,

441
00:23:10,489 --> 00:23:13,492
it's boring to sit there
and stabilize an airplane.

442
00:23:13,492 --> 00:23:20,999
And you can see there on the
plane up here, em, there is, em,

443
00:23:20,999 --> 00:23:23,001
Eh, Sperry's son
is sitting there

444
00:23:23,001 --> 00:23:26,004
and they put an autopilot
on this plane

445
00:23:26,004 --> 00:23:30,642
and, em, eh, th-th-the mechanic was walking on the wing

446
00:23:30,642 --> 00:23:32,377
to introduce a perturbation

447
00:23:32,377 --> 00:23:34,713
and you can see that it's
pretty close to the ground.

448
00:23:34,713 --> 00:23:38,817
So i-in-in, around 1913
this autopilot

449
00:23:38,817 --> 00:23:42,487
won the prize for the most stable airplane at, eh,

450
00:23:42,487 --> 00:23:43,488
in Paris.

451
00:23:43,488 --> 00:23:45,490
And I've taken this
from the Honeywell book.

452
00:23:45,490 --> 00:23:46,491
In that they say,

453
00:23:46,491 --> 00:23:48,794
"An interesting feature is
the proximity to the ground."

454
00:23:48,794 --> 00:23:50,462
(laughing)

455
00:23:50,462 --> 00:23:54,866
And down there on the left you can see the Wright Brothers

456
00:23:54,866 --> 00:23:58,370
and then you can see,
em, eh, Minorsky

457
00:23:58,370 --> 00:24:02,474
who was a ship engineer, eh, who was very heavily involved

458
00:24:02,474 --> 00:24:05,143
in the interaction between stability and control.

459
00:24:06,711 --> 00:24:09,548
Here's another field, telecommunications.

460
00:24:09,548 --> 00:24:14,052
Em, the problem was how can you
communicate over long distances?

461
00:24:14,052 --> 00:24:16,054
And to do this you
needed amplification.

462
00:24:16,054 --> 00:24:19,424
So you needed to make
a good amplifier.

463
00:24:19,424 --> 00:24:22,060
We are not talking
about 1920, 1930.

464
00:24:22,060 --> 00:24:24,863
And their amp, the amplifying device at that time

465
00:24:24,863 --> 00:24:28,333
was the electronic tube,
a pretty crummy device.

466
00:24:28,333 --> 00:24:29,534
It gave you amplification,

467
00:24:29,534 --> 00:24:30,869
but it was non-linear

468
00:24:30,869 --> 00:24:33,572
and it had time
bearing characteristic.

469
00:24:33,572 --> 00:24:35,807
And then we had some brilliant
people who we, eh,

470
00:24:35,807 --> 00:24:39,177
at Bell Labs invented
the feedback amplifier.

471
00:24:39,177 --> 00:24:42,414
So what did, eh,
it was done by Black.

472
00:24:42,414 --> 00:24:44,916
And the idea was that,

473
00:24:44,916 --> 00:24:48,753
how can you make a system out
a bad component?

474
00:24:48,753 --> 00:24:50,222
And the-uh-the answer was

475
00:24:50,222 --> 00:24:52,691
by using feedback
you can actually do this.

476
00:24:52,691 --> 00:24:54,693
And you see this
calculation down here

477
00:24:54,693 --> 00:24:56,194
for a feedback amplifier,

478
00:24:56,194 --> 00:24:59,231
that, eh, if you, if-arrange a feedback in here,

479
00:24:59,231 --> 00:25:01,266
you look at the-the gain.

480
00:25:01,266 --> 00:25:03,969
It's essentially if k is
large, the gain is large.

481
00:25:03,969 --> 00:25:05,437
These two terms disappeared

482
00:25:05,437 --> 00:25:08,607
and essentially R2 over R1
which are passive component.

483
00:25:08,607 --> 00:25:12,277
So that was the key idea
of the feedback amplifier.

484
00:25:12,277 --> 00:25:14,679
Of course, again, people run
into stability problems.

485
00:25:14,679 --> 00:25:16,248
Here they call it singing

486
00:25:16,248 --> 00:25:19,184
because this amplifier
started to, y'know,

487
00:25:19,184 --> 00:25:21,186
this sort of sound you had here in the beginning

488
00:25:21,186 --> 00:25:23,455
with the microphone
and the loud speaker.

489
00:25:23,455 --> 00:25:25,590
So therefore you had to do
stability theory

490
00:25:25,590 --> 00:25:26,958
and there are two giants.

491
00:25:26,958 --> 00:25:31,429
Bode, who I was told grew up
here in Urbana,

492
00:25:31,429 --> 00:25:36,167
and, em, eh, his father was a professor here in

493
00:25:36,167 --> 00:25:37,502
classics or languages,

494
00:25:37,502 --> 00:25:39,738
and there were Harry Nyquist who grew up in Sweden.

495
00:25:42,507 --> 00:25:44,643
Eh, the reason why feedback
is used so much

496
00:25:44,643 --> 00:25:47,078
that that's a tremendous power.

497
00:25:47,078 --> 00:25:49,781
You can make accurate system
from imprecise component

498
00:25:49,781 --> 00:25:52,017
like you did
in electronic amplifiers.

499
00:25:52,017 --> 00:25:53,852
You can reduce effects
of disturbances

500
00:25:53,852 --> 00:25:56,721
and component variation
like you do in process control.

501
00:25:56,721 --> 00:25:59,758
You can regulate, stabilize,
and shape behavior.

502
00:25:59,758 --> 00:26:01,192
You're a fantastic properties.

503
00:26:01,192 --> 00:26:03,028
So what are the drawbacks?

504
00:26:03,028 --> 00:26:05,830
Drawback number one
is risk for instability.

505
00:26:05,830 --> 00:26:09,501
And that's why stability has played such an important role

506
00:26:09,501 --> 00:26:11,303
in control engineering.

507
00:26:11,303 --> 00:26:13,305
Y'know, you really
have to know,

508
00:26:13,305 --> 00:26:15,173
you have to know your enemies.

