00:29:27,665 --> 00:29:29,667
We got journals
and we got conferences

591
00:29:29,667 --> 00:29:33,838
and I think today, there's a control conference every week.

592
00:29:33,872 --> 00:29:36,407
I think every subject
would have been proud of this,

593
00:29:36,407 --> 00:29:38,710
and we are now come
roughly to 1960.

594
00:29:40,445 --> 00:29:44,716
So, in 1960 I said we
had a paradigm shift.

595
00:29:44,716 --> 00:29:46,985
And in my mind
the driver was a space race.

596
00:29:46,985 --> 00:29:49,721
You know Sputnik came up 1957,

597
00:29:49,721 --> 00:29:52,323
generated a fantastic
amount of activity.

598
00:29:52,323 --> 00:29:54,859
Another thing that came
around were the computers.

599
00:29:54,859 --> 00:29:58,429
So one started to use computers
to solve control,

600
00:29:58,429 --> 00:30:00,098
to implement control systems

601
00:30:00,098 --> 00:30:02,100
instead of using
analog computers.

602
00:30:02,100 --> 00:30:05,036
And the first installation
was i-was in an oil refinery

603
00:30:05,036 --> 00:30:07,172
in Texas in '59.

604
00:30:07,172 --> 00:30:11,009
Eh, also it was discovered that the tools that were available

605
00:30:11,009 --> 00:30:13,945
at the time, in 1960
were insufficient.

606
00:30:13,945 --> 00:30:16,714
So what happened then,
we turned a lot to mathematics

607
00:30:16,714 --> 00:30:19,184
to bring in, y'know,
new tools and new ideas.

608
00:30:19,184 --> 00:30:22,053
There was a rapid growth
of s-subspecialties,

609
00:30:22,053 --> 00:30:26,191
optimal control, stochastic control, nonlinear control, etc.

610
00:30:26,191 --> 00:30:28,193
We also got computational tools.

611
00:30:28,193 --> 00:30:29,627
Y'know, MATLAB today is a

612
00:30:29,627 --> 00:30:32,096
successor of what was
developed at the time.

613
00:30:32,096 --> 00:30:34,866
There was a very impressive
development of theory,

614
00:30:34,866 --> 00:30:38,703
but the holistic view was lost.

615
00:30:38,703 --> 00:30:41,306
Eh, I've sometimes
said at the time that, em,

616
00:30:41,306 --> 00:30:43,408
there were many professors
of control

617
00:30:43,408 --> 00:30:47,879
who had a platonic view
of control systems.

618
00:30:47,879 --> 00:30:50,381
They talked a lot about them,
but they never touched them.

619
00:30:50,381 --> 00:30:51,816
[laughing]

620
00:30:51,816 --> 00:30:54,819
And, em, that illustrates, y'know, the, uh, lack of the

621
00:30:54,819 --> 00:30:56,888
holistic view.

622
00:30:56,888 --> 00:30:58,556
Eh, I'll give you a
couple of examples.

623
00:30:58,556 --> 00:31:01,025
One of the most promising one-eh, p-prominent one

624
00:31:01,025 --> 00:31:02,994
was optimal control theory.

625
00:31:02,994 --> 00:31:06,497
Eh, it was built on-on, eh, classical results,

626
00:31:06,497 --> 00:31:09,434
like by Hamilton and Euler.

627
00:31:09,434 --> 00:31:12,270
And then we had Bellman who
developed dynamic programming,

628
00:31:12,270 --> 00:31:14,272
direct descendant
of Hamilton and Jacobi.

629
00:31:14,272 --> 00:31:16,708
We had Pontryagin,
who you can say,

630
00:31:16,708 --> 00:31:18,710
his ideas were direct descendents

631
00:31:18,710 --> 00:31:19,711
of Euler and Lagrange.

632
00:31:19,711 --> 00:31:21,913
And today we have what you
call model predictive control.

633
00:31:21,913 --> 00:31:24,048
A lot of this was driven
by the space race.

634
00:31:24,048 --> 00:31:26,150
Y'know, you would like to
shoot up a heavy satellite

635
00:31:26,150 --> 00:31:27,418
with a weak rocket,

636
00:31:27,418 --> 00:31:30,154
you better do it
in the right way.

637
00:31:30,154 --> 00:31:32,156
Eh, and here I just gave
two books,

638
00:31:32,156 --> 00:31:34,025
one by Bellman
and one by Pontryagin.

639
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:37,362
Another very important
thing that happened

640
00:31:37,362 --> 00:31:38,630
was the Kalman filtering.

641
00:31:38,630 --> 00:31:40,365
And I put Wiener
right on the left

642
00:31:40,365 --> 00:31:42,634
because Wiener filtering
was the predecessor.

643
00:31:42,634 --> 00:31:46,471
In-in many senses a lot of the
machine was developed by him.

644
00:31:46,471 --> 00:31:48,239
And then Kalman came along

645
00:31:48,239 --> 00:31:52,310
and found very efficient ways
to filter signals

646
00:31:52,310 --> 00:31:54,312
and he could
combine measurements

647
00:31:54,312 --> 00:31:57,715
with mathematical models to
es-to do estimation.

648
00:31:57,715 --> 00:31:59,717
So that's the basis
of the Kalman filtering.

649
00:31:59,717 --> 00:32:01,986
Another thing is that we also
got a new structure

650
00:32:01,986 --> 00:32:03,187
of the controller.

651
00:32:03,187 --> 00:32:05,590
Instead of the controller
being a black box,

652
00:32:05,590 --> 00:32:06,791
we now saw that the controller

653
00:32:06,791 --> 00:32:08,793
should have a couple
of components,

654
00:32:08,793 --> 00:32:09,794
a Kalman filter, here,

655
00:32:09,794 --> 00:32:12,030
that receives all the
information from the process.

656
00:32:12,030 --> 00:32:14,899
It generates, best
estimate of the state.

657
00:32:14,899 --> 00:32:18,703
Then we have here a feedforward
generator that-that generates

658
00:32:18,703 --> 00:32:20,772
both feedforward signal, that drives the system

659
00:32:20,772 --> 00:32:21,973
where we would like it to go

660
00:32:21,973 --> 00:32:25,143
and also desire-generates desired behavior of the state

661
00:32:25,143 --> 00:32:27,345
and then we just do
state feedback up here.

662
00:32:27,345 --> 00:32:31,482
So, that was something that we
got out of the Kalman's work

663
00:32:31,482 --> 00:32:32,483
and the Kalman filtering.

664
00:32:34,319 --> 00:32:36,454
We also got system
identification,

665
00:32:36,454 --> 00:32:38,990
a methodology to get out mathematical models

666
00:32:38,990 --> 00:32:40,525
from experiments.

667
00:32:40,525 --> 00:32:44,462
This is data I made myself in a
paper factory in the early 60s.

668
00:32:44,462 --> 00:32:46,130
We which-we, uh, wanted to know

669
00:32:46,130 --> 00:32:49,200
how does a big factory
behave from input/output

670
00:32:49,200 --> 00:32:51,202
and then you persuade the people

671
00:32:51,202 --> 00:32:53,338
to let you change things
during production

672
00:32:53,338 --> 00:32:56,140
and you measure important variables in the end.

673
00:32:56,140 --> 00:33:00,044
And then based on this data
you, em, eh, you estimate

674
00:33:00,044 --> 00:33:02,580
mathematical relations
between these ones.

675
00:33:02,580 --> 00:33:05,817
And the typical idea is that
by-by doing better control

676
00:33:05,817 --> 00:33:07,685
you can move closer to tolerances here

677
00:33:07,685 --> 00:33:09,153
and you can save money.

678
00:33:09,153 --> 00:33:11,923
So here's a tip, one of the first experiments we did

679
00:33:11,923 --> 00:33:14,592
when we were controlling the thickness of paper accurately.

680
00:33:14,592 --> 00:33:16,861
It was a project that IBM
was running together

681
00:33:16,861 --> 00:33:18,096
with the Swedish paper mill.

682
00:33:19,330 --> 00:33:21,265
Here's another area,
adaptive control.

683
00:33:23,501 --> 00:33:27,505
Em, one of the things, eh, it actually came up, er,

684
00:33:27,505 --> 00:33:29,340
from aerospace

685
00:33:29,340 --> 00:33:32,377
because when airplanes
started to go supersonic,

686
00:33:32,377 --> 00:33:34,345
the dynamics changed.

687
00:33:34,345 --> 00:33:35,513
And then it was not enough

688
00:33:35,513 --> 00:33:37,515
to have an autopilot
with fixed settings

689
00:33:37,515 --> 00:33:41,119
so one tried to do an autopilot that could adjust itself

690
00:33:41,119 --> 00:33:42,954
to changing flight conditions.

691
00:33:42,954 --> 00:33:45,189
The early experiments
were not too successful.

692
00:33:45,189 --> 00:33:47,892
There was a famous crash
on the X-15, for example.

693
00:33:47,892 --> 00:33:49,861
So the field has been
going up and down

694
00:33:49,861 --> 00:33:51,696
and has continued
to go up and down.

695
00:33:51,696 --> 00:33:53,564
Eh, one of the things
I've been concerned with

696
00:33:53,564 --> 00:33:56,033
was called
the self-tuning regulator.

697
00:33:56,033 --> 00:33:57,702
Eh, there was a lot of
theory developed.

698
00:33:57,702 --> 00:33:59,337
There were case studies.

699
00:33:59,337 --> 00:34:01,305
Eh, I've given here
a couple of products

700
00:34:01,305 --> 00:34:03,474
that I will skip
because of time.

701
00:34:03,474 --> 00:34:04,642
I'll give you one
example, though.

702
00:34:04,642 --> 00:34:06,744
A ship steering autopilot.

703
00:34:06,744 --> 00:34:08,980
This was something
we developed from my lab

704
00:34:08,980 --> 00:34:11,449
together with a local
shipyard in Kockums.

705
00:34:11,449 --> 00:34:12,984
And when I Google this now,

706
00:34:12,984 --> 00:34:16,320
the autopilot is still marketed by Northrop Grumman.

707
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:18,189
And here I gave you an example.

708
00:34:18,189 --> 00:34:20,825
A typical autopilot
runs a PID controller,

709
00:34:20,825 --> 00:34:22,827
and here you see
what is happening,

710
00:34:22,827 --> 00:34:24,929
how the course is deviating

711
00:34:24,929 --> 00:34:27,031
when you're running
in pretty bad weather

712
00:34:27,031 --> 00:34:29,434
and here you see
what the rudder is doing.

713
00:34:29,434 --> 00:34:31,969
When we switched on the adaptive
controller in here,

714
00:34:31,969 --> 00:34:35,006
you see what happens to
the course deviations.

715
00:34:35,006 --> 00:34:37,275
You don't have to do an analysis
to see that this is better.

716
00:34:37,275 --> 00:34:40,778
The reason that the adaptive
controller can do it here,

717
00:34:40,778 --> 00:34:41,979
it knows about waves

