1418
01:02:53,369 --> 01:02:55,838
Incidentally, I borrowed this
from Bruce Krogh at,

1419
01:02:55,838 --> 01:02:57,173
eh, Carnegie Mellon.

1420
01:02:57,173 --> 01:02:58,474
So what control engineers do,

1421
01:02:58,474 --> 01:03:00,042
they work with
stability feedback,

1422
01:03:00,042 --> 01:03:01,978
ordinary differential equation, moderate complexity,

1423
01:03:01,978 --> 01:03:03,513
and worry about robustness.

1424
01:03:03,513 --> 01:03:05,515
And then they write a-a Simulink simulation.

1425
01:03:05,515 --> 01:03:07,517
They throw this over
to the computing guys.

1426
01:03:07,517 --> 01:03:09,152
And they know about
languages, etc,

1427
01:03:09,152 --> 01:03:11,521
formal methods,
abstraction, architecture.

1428
01:03:11,521 --> 01:03:13,523
And then they take the
simulating program

1429
01:03:13,523 --> 01:03:15,858
and then they do some kind
of software for it.

1430
01:03:15,858 --> 01:03:17,793
And, eh, sometimes it works.

1431
01:03:17,793 --> 01:03:19,162
Sometimes it doesn't work.

1432
01:03:19,162 --> 01:03:20,163
So what's happening here,

1433
01:03:20,163 --> 01:03:21,864
control engineers have to know

1434
01:03:21,864 --> 01:03:23,866
a little bit more
about computing.

1435
01:03:23,866 --> 01:03:25,868
Computing engineers have
to know more about control.

1436
01:03:25,868 --> 01:03:27,136
I'll give you one example.

1437
01:03:27,136 --> 01:03:30,239
In automotive now there is a
communications device

1438
01:03:30,239 --> 01:03:33,709
called the can bus which is a standard communication

1439
01:03:33,709 --> 01:03:35,044
protocol in the cars.

1440
01:03:35,044 --> 01:03:37,046
It's a beautiful
little protocol,

1441
01:03:37,046 --> 01:03:38,614
but it has one drawback.

1442
01:03:38,614 --> 01:03:40,650
It has time delays,
and not only that,

1443
01:03:40,650 --> 01:03:43,085
it has very big time delays.

1444
01:03:43,085 --> 01:03:46,022
And if I said that time delays
are bad for control system,

1445
01:03:46,022 --> 01:03:48,024
very big time delays
are really bad.

1446
01:03:48,024 --> 01:03:49,859
So if this person who did
the can bus

1447
01:03:49,859 --> 01:03:51,861
had had a good introductory course in control,

1448
01:03:51,861 --> 01:03:53,696
I said just an introductory course in control,

1449
01:03:53,696 --> 01:03:54,697
that was good.

1450
01:03:54,697 --> 01:03:56,199
He would have known,

1451
01:03:56,199 --> 01:03:57,366
time delays are bad.

1452
01:03:57,366 --> 01:03:59,035
So this would not be.
a good thing

1453
01:03:59,035 --> 01:04:00,436
if you're gonna close
control loops.

1454
01:04:00,436 --> 01:04:01,837
It's alright
if you're gonna just

1455
01:04:01,837 --> 01:04:03,306
raise your windows up and down,

1456
01:04:03,306 --> 01:04:04,307
but if you're going to close

1457
01:04:04,307 --> 01:04:06,976
control feedback loops around there, it's not a good idea.

1458
01:04:06,976 --> 01:04:08,344
So that's one example,

1459
01:04:08,344 --> 01:04:12,415
that could have been
prohibited by good education.

1460
01:04:12,415 --> 01:04:13,382
[laughing]

1461
01:04:13,382 --> 01:04:15,685
I should also mention computing.

1462
01:04:15,685 --> 01:04:16,752
And I still remember,

1463
01:04:16,752 --> 01:04:18,888
eh, well you can start with Vannevar Bush.

1464
01:04:18,888 --> 01:04:21,157
He said, "Engineering can
progress no faster

1465
01:04:21,157 --> 01:04:23,159
"than mathematical analysis
on which it's based.

1466
01:04:23,159 --> 01:04:25,861
"Formal mathematics
is frequently inadequate.

1467
01:04:25,861 --> 01:04:28,464
"A mechanical solution offers the most promise."

1468
01:04:28,464 --> 01:04:30,466
He was at MIT and then
he went ahead and built

1469
01:04:30,466 --> 01:04:32,468
The Mechanical
Differential Analyzer,

1470
01:04:32,468 --> 01:04:36,906
that could solve about six ordinary differential equations.

1471
01:04:36,906 --> 01:04:38,741
I worked for IBM research,
and my boss,

1472
01:04:38,741 --> 01:04:40,343
I was in the math department
for a while,

1473
01:04:40,343 --> 01:04:42,245
my boss was Herman Goldstine.

1474
01:04:42,245 --> 01:04:44,614
He built the first computer
together with John von Neumann.

1475
01:04:44,614 --> 01:04:46,349
So, he was chair
in the math department.

1476
01:04:46,349 --> 01:04:47,683
At one staff meeting
he said this,

1477
01:04:47,683 --> 01:04:48,718
which I've never forgotten.

1478
01:04:48,718 --> 01:04:51,587
"When things change
by two orders of magnitude

1479
01:04:51,587 --> 01:04:53,990
"it is not evolution,
it is revolution."

1480
01:04:55,191 --> 01:04:56,692
Now you combine this
with Moore's Law,

1481
01:04:56,692 --> 01:04:58,361
you get a revolution
every ten years.

1482
01:04:58,361 --> 01:04:59,462
[laughing]

1483
01:04:59,462 --> 01:05:01,464
So, you recognize that
computing power

1484
01:05:01,464 --> 01:05:03,966
changes by two orders
of magnitude roughly speaking

1485
01:05:03,966 --> 01:05:04,800
every ten years.

1486
01:05:04,800 --> 01:05:06,602
And that's why I have to
exchange laptops

1487
01:05:06,602 --> 01:05:08,471
every third year, for example.

1488
01:05:08,471 --> 01:05:10,306
And, eh, there's a
tremendous potential.

1489
01:05:10,306 --> 01:05:11,474
If you think about this, y'know,

1490
01:05:11,474 --> 01:05:14,910
that you're gaining two orders of magnitude per ten years,

1491
01:05:14,910 --> 01:05:16,912
so there's
